n countries}}\n{{Council of Europe}}\n{{European Union candidates}}\n{{La Francophonie}}\n{{Central European Free Trade Agreement}}\n{{OSCE}}\n}}\n{{Coord|41.6|21.7|display=title|dim:180km}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:North Macedonia| ]]\n[[Category:Balkan countries]]\n[[Category:Landlocked countries]]\n[[Category:Member states of the Council of Europe]]\n[[Category:Member states of the Organisation internationale de la Francophonie]]\n[[Category:Member states of the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Member states of NATO]]\n[[Category:Republics]]\n[[Category:Southeastern European countries]]\n[[Category:Southern European countries]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1991]]\n[[Category:1991 establishments in the Republic of Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Countries in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "MarkH21", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKingdoms of Serbia and Yugoslavia:stray brace", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Macedonia"}
{"title_page": "Astor Place station", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Manhattan}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Astor Place\n| former = Astor Place \u2013 Cooper Union<br>Cooper Union\n| bg_color = #007527\n| image = Astor Place 4 vc.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = Downtown platform\n| address = Astor Place &amp; Lafayette Street<br>New York, NY 10003\n| borough = [[Manhattan]]\n| locale = [[NoHo, Manhattan|NoHo]] / [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|43|47|N|73|59|30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = IRT\n| line = [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]]\n| service = Lexington local\n| service_header = Lexington local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|M1|M2|M3|M8}}\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 407\n| accessible = mezzanine\n| acc_note = Elevator is present only in the southbound direction during [[Kmart]] operating hours\n| passengers = 5,111,358<ref>{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -2.6\n| rank = 86\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1904|Oct|27|mf=yes|p=yes}}<ref name=145th />\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=14th Street \u2013 Union Square | line=IRT Lexington Avenue Line | service=Lexington local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=Bleecker Street | line=IRT Lexington Avenue Line | service=Lexington local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n| embedded = <hr>{{Infobox NRHP\n| embed = yes\n| name = Astor Place Subway Station (IRT)\n| added = September 17, 2004\n| mpsub = New York City Subway System MPS\n| refnum = 04001013<ref name=\"focus\">{{Cite web |url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov |title=NPS Focus |work=National Register of Historic Places |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| designated_other2 = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = November 24, 1981<ref name=\"NYCL-1096\">{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1096.pdf|title=Interborough Rapid Transit System, Underground Interior|date=November 24, 1981|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_number = 1096\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_color = #FFE978\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Astor Place''', also called '''Astor Place \u2013 Cooper Union''' on signs, is a local station on the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Completed in 1904, it is one of the [[History of the IRT subway before 1918|original twenty-eight stations]] in the system. Located at the intersection of [[Lafayette Street (Manhattan)|Lafayette Street]], [[Eighth Street (Manhattan)|Eighth Street]], [[Fourth Avenue (Manhattan)|Fourth Avenue]], [[Cooper Square]], and [[Astor Place]] between the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] and [[NoHo, Manhattan|NoHo]], it is served by the {{NYCS|6}} train at all times, the [[6d (New York City Subway service)|&lt;6&gt;]] train during weekdays in the peak direction, and by the {{NYCS|4}} train during late nights. The station is on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n== History ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|Lexington}}\n|title-color=white\n|style=margin-left:10px;margin-top:10px;float:right;\n|legend =track\n|map=\nnumN345\nuvSTR!~MFADEg\\uvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[14th Street\u2013Union Square (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|14 St]]\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nd\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\nd\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\d\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\d\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nuvSTR!~MFADEf\\uvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Bleecker Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|Bleecker St]]\n}}\n}}\nConstruction started on the [[Early history of the IRT subway|first IRT line]] in 1900.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Rapid_Transit_Tunnel_Begun_-_Ground_Officially_Broken_(1900)| title=Rapid Transit Tunnel Begun - Ground Officially Broken (1900)| work=www.nycsubway.org}}</ref> The part of the line from City Hall to just south of 42nd Street was part of the original [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] line including the Astor Place station, opened on October 27, 1904.<ref name=\"145th\">{{Cite news|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1904/10/28/118948832.html|title=Our Subway Open: 150,000 Try It; Mayor McClellan Runs the First Official Train.|date=October 28, 1904|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 21, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|page=1}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] listed the station among the 69 most deteriorated stations in the subway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/06/11/nyregion/agency-lists-its-69-most-deteriorated-subway-stations.html|title=Agency Lists Its 69 Most Deteriorated Subway Stations| date=June 11, 1981| newspaper=The New York Times| last1=Gargan| first1=Edward A.| accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> The station underwent [[renovation]] from June 1984 to May 1986. The station was renovated for $2.5 million, and was part of the Adopt-a-Station program. The money included $600,000 from the Federal Urban Mass Transit Administration, $125,000 from private sources, including some from the Vincent Astor Foundation. The scope of the project included the restoration of the famous glazed ceramic beaver plaques, new improved lighting, the installation of noise-abatement material, as well as the installation of new brown floor tiles. A new piece of porcelain steel artwork by [[Cooper Union]] alumnus [[Milton Glaser]] was installed, and a cast-iron copy of one of the station's original kiosks was built. There was an underpass between the uptown and downtown sides, but it was closed and covered up in the 1980s renovation.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/17/nyregion/refurbishing-of-irt-station-applauded-by-well-wishers.html| title=Refurbishing of IRT Station Applauded by Well-Wishers| last=Blau| first=Eleanor| date=May 17, 1986| newspaper=The New York Times| issn=0362-4331| access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe original plans for the [[Hudson and Manhattan Railroad]] (now [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|PATH]]) included a spur along Ninth Street to this station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/digital/collections/cul/texts/ldpd_6282382_000/ldpd_6282382_000.pdf|title=Map of Hudson & Manhattan Railroad Hudson Tunnel System|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1912|website=columbia.edu|publisher=Hudson & Manhattan Railroad|access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IRT Lexington Avenue Line/Park Avenue South stations}}\nAstor Place is a local station with four tracks and two [[side platform]]s. The [[fare control]] is at platform level, and the underpass connecting northbound and southbound sides was removed in the 1980s. The access hatch to the underpass is visible behind the northbound token booth inside the fare control area. The northbound platform contains a news and candy stand, which replaced the original public women's lavatory. On the southbound side, the station has a department store entrance into a [[K-Mart]]. This store was originally constructed in 1868 as an [[A. T. Stewart]]. It had changed ownership and was a [[Wanamaker's]] when the station was constructed. The heavy brick-faced square columns on the downtown platform support the store above. The northern building of Wanamaker's store, but not the southern building above, burned in the 1950s. Octagonal windows on the brick wall of the platform were the store's showcases.\n\nPlaques of [[beaver]]s are located on the walls, in honor of [[John Jacob Astor]]'s fortune derived from the beaver-pelt trade. The plaques, as well as name tablets, were made by the [[Grueby Faience Company]] in 1904. During the renovation, the magnificent maroon and gold tile [[Cooper Union]] signs underneath the tile Astor Place signs were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/85071996@N00/4017302543/sizes/l/in/pool-1194454@N25/ |title=1982 Photo of Astor Place Signage |year=1982 |work=Cable (Cooper Union Yearbook) |accessdate=December 9, 2009 }}</ref> Black and white pillar signs read Astor Place on one pillar, then Cooper Union on the next.\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station has two entrances, one in each direction. The southbound platform's entrance is at the southwest corner of Astor Place and Lafayette Street, while the northbound platform's entrance is in the traffic island bounded by Fourth Avenue, Lafayette Street, and Eighth Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: East Village|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M05_East%20Village_2015.pdf |website=mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 19, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> There is a reproduction of an [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] entry kiosk on the street level over the northbound entrance.\n\n== Points of interest ==\nThe station itself is a point of local interest, as it is on the [[List of Registered Historic Places in New York#New York County|List of Registered Historic Places in New York]]. Several other sites of historical and cultural importance are located near the station. The [[New York University]] and [[Cooper Union]] are both located nearby. Visitors to the Astor Place area often rotate the [[Alamo (sculpture)|Alamo]] Cube, at street level above the tail end of the northbound platform.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M05_East%20Village_2015.pdf|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: East Village|last=|first=|date=2015|website=mta.info| publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref> A tiled-up doorway, on southwest wall behind the southbound token booth, sports a [[lintel]] proclaiming \"Clinton Hall\". This doorway once led to the [[New York Mercantile Library]] in the former [[Astor Opera House]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://forgotten-ny.com/1998/04/the-other-door-to-nowhere-not-to-be-outdone-the-astor-place-station-irt-6-has-its-very-own-door-to-nowhere-where-did-it-go/| title=Clinton Hall at Astor Place| website=Forgotten New York}}</ref> Other points of interest include:\n\n* [[McSorley's Old Ale House]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[41 Cooper Square|Cooper Union New Academic Building]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Cooper Square Hotel]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Public Theater]] ([[Astor Library]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Colonnade Row]] / [[Astor Place Theatre]] ([[Blue Man Group]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Kmart]] (former [[Wanamaker's|Wanamaker Department Store Annex]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Hamilton Fish House]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\nThe [[Eighth Street \u2013 New York University (BMT Broadway Line)|Eighth Street \u2013 New York University]] station on the [[BMT Broadway Line]] is one block west of the station.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\n== Image gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Astor Place Downtown.JPG|Downtown entrance\nFile:LozDSC00111.jpg|Uptown entrance, a reproduction of an old IRT kiosk\nFile:Astor Place IRT 004 crop.jpg|Faience plaque with beaver, by Heins & LaFarge / Grueby Faience Company, 1904. The [[John Jacob Astor|Astor]] fortune was based on trading beaver pelts\nFile:Astor Place IRT 006.JPG|Faience name tablet by Heins & LaFarge / Grueby Faience Company, 1904.\nFile:Astor Place IRT 002.JPG|Tile with initial \"A\"\nFile:Astor Place IRT 008.JPG|Former women's restroom converted into newsstand\nFile:Astor Place 3 vc.jpg|Columns with alternating ''Astor Place'' and ''Cooper Union'' sign plates\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last=Stookey | first=Lee | title=Subway ceramics : a history and iconography of mosaic and bas relief signs and plaques in the New York City subway system | publisher=L. Stookey | publication-place=Brattleboro, Vt | year=1994 | isbn=978-0-9635486-1-0 | oclc=31901471 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Astor Place (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?5:542|IRT East Side Line|Astor Place}}\n* nycsubway.org \u2014 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?76 Untitled Artwork by Milton Glaser (1986)]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204052106/http://www.stationreporter.net/6train.htm 6 Train]\n* Forgotten NY: Subways and Trains \u2014 [http://forgotten-ny.com/2006/01/the-original-28-part-1-a-look-at-the-artwork-from-the-nycs-first-28-stations-opened-october-27-1904-2/ Original 28 IRT subway stations] \n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606071634/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=6&station=16&xdev=1683 Astor Place (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.730088,-73.990645&spn=0.003846,0.013433&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.730015,-73.990675&panoid=SUtYhTAmboeVC1Kz7QR7QQ&cbp=12,294.46,,0,3.06 Fourth Avenue entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ll=40.730064,-73.991193&spn=0.002976,0.009645&layer=c&cbll=40.730119,-73.991324&panoid=_lQs4as9LfjUGFRgw81tEg&cbp=12,234.59,,0,10.47&t=m&z=17 Lafayette Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [http://www.google.com/maps/@40.7300707,-73.991069,3a,75y,181.85h,90.73t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-LxFHT4_LnBA%2FVe5KiAQz9vI%2FAAAAAAAAsXo%2FAQrlnAFkkAg!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-LxFHT4_LnBA%2FVe5KiAQz9vI%2FAAAAAAAAsXo%2FAQrlnAFkkAg%2Fw203-h101-n-k-no%2F!7i8704!8i4352?hl=en Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.7300854,-73.9912633,3a,75y,346.23h,87.97t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-b1wj2dVxL7o%2FVhvGwjrHJXI%2FAAAAAAAA5Mo%2FqEy-inq-lzYqyqgTKrjlwbOrIgx5lmTWgCLIB!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-b1wj2dVxL7o%2FVhvGwjrHJXI%2FAAAAAAAA5Mo%2FqEy-inq-lzYqyqgTKrjlwbOrIgx5lmTWgCLIB%2Fw203-h100-k-no-pi0-ya350.7274-ro-0-fo100%2F!7i8704!8i4352!6m1!1e1 Lobby and Kmart entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l6=yes|l6x=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|lexington=yes}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:IRT Lexington Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:East Village, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Railway and subway stations on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n[[Category:1904 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations at university and college campuses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Short description|New York City Subway station in Manhattan}}\n{{Infobox NYCS\n| name = Astor Place\n| former = Astor Place \u2013 Cooper Union<br>Cooper Union\n| bg_color = #007527\n| image = Astor Place 4 vc.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = Downtown platform\n| address = Astor Place &amp; Lafayette Street<br>New York, NY 10003\n| borough = [[Manhattan]]\n| locale = [[NoHo, Manhattan|NoHo]] / [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|40|43|47|N|73|59|30|W|display=inline,title}}\n| lat_dir = N\n| lon_dir = W\n| division = IRT\n| line = [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]]\n| service = Lexington local\n| service_header = Lexington local header\n| connection = {{bus icon}} '''[[NYCT Bus]]''': {{NYC bus link|M1|M2|M3|M8}}\n| platforms = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| tracks = 4\n| structure = Underground\n| wifi = yes\n| code = 407\n| accessible = mezzanine\n| acc_note = Elevator is present only in the southbound direction during [[Kmart]] operating hours\n| passengers = 5,111,358<ref>{{NYCS const|riderref}}</ref>\n| pass_year = 2018\n| pass_percent = -2.6\n| rank = 86\n| open_date = {{start date and age|1904|Oct|27|mf=yes|p=yes}}<ref name=145th />\n| next_north = {{NYCS next | station=14th Street \u2013 Union Square | line=IRT Lexington Avenue Line | service=Lexington local}}\n| next_south = {{NYCS next | station=Bleecker Street | line=IRT Lexington Avenue Line | service=Lexington local}}\n| legend = {{NYCS infobox legend|alltimes}}{{NYCS infobox legend|nightsonly}}{{NYCS infobox legend|rushpeak}}\n| embedded = <hr>{{Infobox NRHP\n| embed = yes\n| name = Astor Place Subway Station (IRT)\n| added = September 17, 2004\n| mpsub = New York City Subway System MPS\n| refnum = 04001013<ref name=\"focus\">{{Cite web |url=http://nrhp.focus.nps.gov |title=NPS Focus |work=National Register of Historic Places |publisher=[[National Park Service]] |accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n| designated_other2 = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = November 24, 1981<ref name=\"NYCL-1096\">{{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1096.pdf|title=Interborough Rapid Transit System, Underground Interior|date=November 24, 1981|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>\n| designated_other2_number = 1096\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_color = #FFE978\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Astor Place''', also called '''Astor Place \u2013 Cooper Union''' on signs, is a local station on the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]] of the [[New York City Subway]]. Completed in 1904, it is one of the [[History of the IRT subway before 1918|original twenty-eight stations]] in the system. Located at the intersection of [[Lafayette Street (Manhattan)|Lafayette Street]], [[Eighth Street (Manhattan)|Eighth Street]], [[Fourth Avenue (Manhattan)|Fourth Avenue]], [[Cooper Square]], and [[Astor Place]] between the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] and [[NoHo, Manhattan|NoHo]], it is served by the {{NYCS|6}} train at all times, the [[6d (New York City Subway service)|&lt;6&gt;]] train during weekdays in the peak direction, and by the {{NYCS|4}} train during late nights. The station is on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].\n\n== History ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{Routemap\n|title=Track layout\n|title-bg=#{{NYCS color|Lexington}}\n|title-color=white\n|style=margin-left:10px;margin-top:10px;float:right;\n|legend =track\n|map=\nnumN345\nuvSTR!~MFADEg\\uvSTR!~MFADEg ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[14th Street\u2013Union Square (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|14 St]]\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nd\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\nd\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\dBSr\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\d\ndBSl\\uvSTR\\uvSTR\\d\nuvSTRf\\uvSTRg\nuvSTR!~MFADEf\\uvSTR!~MFADEf ~~ ~~ ~~ to [[Bleecker Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|Bleecker St]]\n}}\n}}\nConstruction started on the [[Early history of the IRT subway|first IRT line]] in 1900.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Rapid_Transit_Tunnel_Begun_-_Ground_Officially_Broken_(1900)| title=Rapid Transit Tunnel Begun - Ground Officially Broken (1900)| work=www.nycsubway.org}}</ref> The part of the line from City Hall to just south of 42nd Street was part of the original [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] line including the Astor Place station, opened on October 27, 1904.<ref name=\"145th\">{{cite news| newspaper=New York Times| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1904/10/28/archives/our-subway-open-150000-try-it-mayor-mcclellan-runs-the-first.html| title=Our Subway Open: 150,000 Try It| date=October 28, 1904| via=NYCSubway.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|MTA]] listed the station among the 69 most deteriorated stations in the subway system.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/06/11/nyregion/agency-lists-its-69-most-deteriorated-subway-stations.html|title=Agency Lists Its 69 Most Deteriorated Subway Stations| date=June 11, 1981| newspaper=The New York Times| last1=Gargan| first1=Edward A.| accessdate=August 13, 2016}}</ref> The station underwent [[renovation]] from June 1984 to May 1986. The station was renovated for $2.5 million, and was part of the Adopt-a-Station program. The money included $600,000 from the Federal Urban Mass Transit Administration, $125,000 from private sources, including some from the Vincent Astor Foundation. The scope of the project included the restoration of the famous glazed ceramic beaver plaques, new improved lighting, the installation of noise-abatement material, as well as the installation of new brown floor tiles. A new piece of porcelain steel artwork by [[Cooper Union]] alumnus [[Milton Glaser]] was installed, and a cast-iron copy of one of the station's original kiosks was built. There was an underpass between the uptown and downtown sides, but it was closed and covered up in the 1980s renovation.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/05/17/nyregion/refurbishing-of-irt-station-applauded-by-well-wishers.html| title=Refurbishing of IRT Station Applauded by Well-Wishers| last=Blau| first=Eleanor| date=May 17, 1986| newspaper=The New York Times| issn=0362-4331| access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe original plans for the [[Hudson and Manhattan Railroad]] (now [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|PATH]]) included a spur along Ninth Street to this station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/lweb/digital/collections/cul/texts/ldpd_6282382_000/ldpd_6282382_000.pdf|title=Map of Hudson & Manhattan Railroad Hudson Tunnel System|last=|first=|date=December 31, 1912|website=columbia.edu|publisher=Hudson & Manhattan Railroad|access-date=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IRT Lexington Avenue Line/Park Avenue South stations}}\nAstor Place is a local station with four tracks and two [[side platform]]s. The [[fare control]] is at platform level, and the underpass connecting northbound and southbound sides was removed in the 1980s. The access hatch to the underpass is visible behind the northbound token booth inside the fare control area. The northbound platform contains a news and candy stand, which replaced the original public women's lavatory. On the southbound side, the station has a department store entrance into a [[K-Mart]]. This store was originally constructed in 1868 as an [[A. T. Stewart]]. It had changed ownership and was a [[Wanamaker's]] when the station was constructed. The heavy brick-faced square columns on the downtown platform support the store above. The northern building of Wanamaker's store, but not the southern building above, burned in the 1950s. Octagonal windows on the brick wall of the platform were the store's showcases.\n\nPlaques of [[beaver]]s are located on the walls, in honor of [[John Jacob Astor]]'s fortune derived from the beaver-pelt trade. The plaques, as well as name tablets, were made by the [[Grueby Faience Company]] in 1904. During the renovation, the magnificent maroon and gold tile [[Cooper Union]] signs underneath the tile Astor Place signs were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/85071996@N00/4017302543/sizes/l/in/pool-1194454@N25/ |title=1982 Photo of Astor Place Signage |year=1982 |work=Cable (Cooper Union Yearbook) |accessdate=December 9, 2009 }}</ref> Black and white pillar signs read Astor Place on one pillar, then Cooper Union on the next.\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Exits===\nThe station has two entrances, one in each direction. The southbound platform's entrance is at the southwest corner of Astor Place and Lafayette Street, while the northbound platform's entrance is in the traffic island bounded by Fourth Avenue, Lafayette Street, and Eighth Street.<ref>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: East Village|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M05_East%20Village_2015.pdf |website=mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 19, 2015|date=2015}}</ref> There is a reproduction of an [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] entry kiosk on the street level over the northbound entrance.\n\n== Points of interest ==\nThe station itself is a point of local interest, as it is on the [[List of Registered Historic Places in New York#New York County|List of Registered Historic Places in New York]]. Several other sites of historical and cultural importance are located near the station. The [[New York University]] and [[Cooper Union]] are both located nearby. Visitors to the Astor Place area often rotate the [[Alamo (sculpture)|Alamo]] Cube, at street level above the tail end of the northbound platform.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M05_East%20Village_2015.pdf|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: East Village|last=|first=|date=2015|website=mta.info| publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|access-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref> A tiled-up doorway, on southwest wall behind the southbound token booth, sports a [[lintel]] proclaiming \"Clinton Hall\". This doorway once led to the [[New York Mercantile Library]] in the former [[Astor Opera House]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://forgotten-ny.com/1998/04/the-other-door-to-nowhere-not-to-be-outdone-the-astor-place-station-irt-6-has-its-very-own-door-to-nowhere-where-did-it-go/| title=Clinton Hall at Astor Place| website=Forgotten New York}}</ref> Other points of interest include:\n\n* [[McSorley's Old Ale House]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[41 Cooper Square|Cooper Union New Academic Building]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Cooper Square Hotel]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Public Theater]] ([[Astor Library]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Colonnade Row]] / [[Astor Place Theatre]] ([[Blue Man Group]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Kmart]] (former [[Wanamaker's|Wanamaker Department Store Annex]])<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n* [[Hamilton Fish House]]<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\nThe [[Eighth Street \u2013 New York University (BMT Broadway Line)|Eighth Street \u2013 New York University]] station on the [[BMT Broadway Line]] is one block west of the station.<ref name=\"MTA-NameofNeighborhood-2015\" />\n\n== Image gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Astor Place Downtown.JPG|Downtown entrance\nFile:LozDSC00111.jpg|Uptown entrance, a reproduction of an old IRT kiosk\nFile:Astor Place IRT 004 crop.jpg|Faience plaque with beaver, by Heins & LaFarge / Grueby Faience Company, 1904. The [[John Jacob Astor|Astor]] fortune was based on trading beaver pelts\nFile:Astor Place IRT 006.JPG|Faience name tablet by Heins & LaFarge / Grueby Faience Company, 1904.\nFile:Astor Place IRT 002.JPG|Tile with initial \"A\"\nFile:Astor Place IRT 008.JPG|Former women's restroom converted into newsstand\nFile:Astor Place 3 vc.jpg|Columns with alternating ''Astor Place'' and ''Cooper Union'' sign plates\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last=Stookey | first=Lee | title=Subway ceramics : a history and iconography of mosaic and bas relief signs and plaques in the New York City subway system | publisher=L. Stookey | publication-place=Brattleboro, Vt | year=1994 | isbn=978-0-9635486-1-0 | oclc=31901471 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Astor Place (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?5:542|IRT East Side Line|Astor Place}}\n* nycsubway.org \u2014 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?76 Untitled Artwork by Milton Glaser (1986)]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204052106/http://www.stationreporter.net/6train.htm 6 Train]\n* Forgotten NY: Subways and Trains \u2014 [http://forgotten-ny.com/2006/01/the-original-28-part-1-a-look-at-the-artwork-from-the-nycs-first-28-stations-opened-october-27-1904-2/ Original 28 IRT subway stations] \n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606071634/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=6&station=16&xdev=1683 Astor Place (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.730088,-73.990645&spn=0.003846,0.013433&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.730015,-73.990675&panoid=SUtYhTAmboeVC1Kz7QR7QQ&cbp=12,294.46,,0,3.06 Fourth Avenue entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ll=40.730064,-73.991193&spn=0.002976,0.009645&layer=c&cbll=40.730119,-73.991324&panoid=_lQs4as9LfjUGFRgw81tEg&cbp=12,234.59,,0,10.47&t=m&z=17 Lafayette Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [http://www.google.com/maps/@40.7300707,-73.991069,3a,75y,181.85h,90.73t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-LxFHT4_LnBA%2FVe5KiAQz9vI%2FAAAAAAAAsXo%2FAQrlnAFkkAg!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh4.googleusercontent.com%2F-LxFHT4_LnBA%2FVe5KiAQz9vI%2FAAAAAAAAsXo%2FAQrlnAFkkAg%2Fw203-h101-n-k-no%2F!7i8704!8i4352?hl=en Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://www.google.com/maps/@40.7300854,-73.9912633,3a,75y,346.23h,87.97t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-b1wj2dVxL7o%2FVhvGwjrHJXI%2FAAAAAAAA5Mo%2FqEy-inq-lzYqyqgTKrjlwbOrIgx5lmTWgCLIB!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-b1wj2dVxL7o%2FVhvGwjrHJXI%2FAAAAAAAA5Mo%2FqEy-inq-lzYqyqgTKrjlwbOrIgx5lmTWgCLIB%2Fw203-h100-k-no-pi0-ya350.7274-ro-0-fo100%2F!7i8704!8i4352!6m1!1e1 Lobby and Kmart entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l6=yes|l6x=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|lexington=yes}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:IRT Lexington Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:East Village, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Railway and subway stations on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n[[Category:1904 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations at university and college campuses]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "format ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astor_Place_station"}
{"title_page": "The Old Man and the Sea", "text_new": "<ref>{{cite web |last1=the old man and the sea |title=the old man and the sea |url=https://summarybook.online/the-old-man-and-the-sea/ |website=summary book}}</ref>{{short description|Novel by Ernest Hemingway}} \n{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = '''The Old Man and the Sea'''\n| image        = Oldmansea.jpg\n| caption      = Original book cover\n| author       = [[Ernest Hemingway]]\n| cover_artist = \n| country      = United States\n| language      = English\n| genre        = Literary Fiction\n| published = 1952 ([[Charles Scribner's Sons]])\n| media_type   = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages        = 127\n| awards = [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (1953)<br> [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] (1954)\n| isbn         = 0-684-80122-1\n| oclc         =\n| dewey        =813.52\n| congress = PS3515.E37\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =}}\n'''''The Old Man and the Sea''''' is a short novel written by the American author [[Ernest Hemingway]] in 1951 in [[Cuba]], and published in 1952.<ref name=\"Time\"/> It was the last major work of fiction by Hemingway that was published during his lifetime. One of his most famous works, it tells the story of Santiago, an aging [[Cubans|Cuban]] [[fisherman]] who struggles with a giant [[marlin]] far out in the [[Gulf Stream]] off the coast of Cuba.<ref name=\"nobel\">{{cite web | title = The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 | work = The Nobel Foundation | url = http://nobelprize.org/literature/laureates/1954/ | accessdate = January 31, 2005 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, ''The Old Man and the Sea'' was awarded the [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]], and it was cited by the [[Nobel Committee]] as contributing to their awarding of the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] to Hemingway in 1954.<ref name=\"nobel\"/>\n\n==Plot summary==\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' tells the story of a battle between an aging, experienced fisherman, Santiago, and a large [[marlin]]. The story opens with Santiago having gone 84 days without catching a fish, and now being seen as \"''salao''{{-\"}}, the worst form of unluckiness. He is so unlucky that his young apprentice, Manolin, has been forbidden by his parents to sail with him and has been told instead to fish with successful fishermen. The boy visits Santiago's shack each night, hauling his fishing gear, preparing food, talking about American baseball and his favorite player, [[Joe DiMaggio]]. Santiago tells Manolin that on the next day, he will venture far out into the Gulf Stream, north of [[Cuba]] in the [[Straits of Florida]] to fish, confident that his unlucky streak is near its end.\n\nOn the eighty-fifth day of his unlucky streak, Santiago takes his [[skiff]] into the Gulf Stream, sets his lines and by noon, has his bait taken by a big fish that he is sure is a [[marlin]]. Unable to haul in the great marlin, Santiago is instead pulled by the marlin, and two days and nights pass with Santiago holding onto the line. Though wounded by the struggle and in pain, Santiago expresses a compassionate appreciation for his adversary, often referring to him as a brother. He also determines that, because of the fish's great dignity, no one shall deserve to eat the marlin.\n\nOn the third day, the fish begins to circle the skiff. Santiago, worn out and almost delirious, uses all his remaining strength to pull the fish onto its side and stab the marlin with a [[harpoon]]. Santiago straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and heads home, thinking about the high price the fish will bring him at the market and how many people he will feed.\n\nOn his way in to shore, [[shark]]s are attracted to the marlin's blood. Santiago kills a great [[mako shark]] with his harpoon, but he loses the weapon. He makes a new harpoon by strapping his knife to the end of an [[oar]] to help ward off the next line of sharks; five sharks are slain and many others are driven away. But the sharks keep coming, and by nightfall the [[sharks]] have almost devoured the marlin's entire carcass, leaving a skeleton consisting mostly of its backbone, its tail, and its head. Santiago knows that he is destroyed and tells the sharks of how they have killed his dreams. Upon reaching the shore before dawn on the next day, Santiago struggles to his shack, carrying the heavy mast on his shoulder, leaving the fish head and the bones on the shore. Once home, he slumps onto his bed and falls into a deep sleep.\n\nA group of fishermen gather the next day around the boat where the fish's skeleton is still attached. One of the fishermen measures it to be {{convert|18|ft|m}} from nose to tail. Pedrico is given the head of the fish, and the other fishermen tell Manolin to tell the old man how sorry they are. Tourists at the nearby caf\u00e9 mistakenly take it for a shark. The boy, worried about the old man, cries upon finding him safe asleep and at his injured hands. Manolin brings him newspapers and coffee. When the old man wakes, they promise to fish together once again. Upon his return to sleep, Santiago dreams of his youth\u2014of lions on an African beach.\n\n==Background and publication==\n{{quote box | width = 22em | quote = No good book has ever been written that has in it symbols arrived at beforehand and stuck in&nbsp;.... I tried to make a real old man, a real boy, a real sea and a real fish and real sharks. But if I made them good and true enough they would mean many things. | source = Ernest Hemingway in 1954<ref>{{cite magazine| url= http://content.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,935439,00.html | title=Books: An American Storyteller | magazine=TIME| date=December 13, 1954| accessdate=February 1, 2011 }}</ref>}}\n\nWritten in 1951, and published in 1952, ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is Hemingway's final full-length work published during his lifetime. The book, dedicated to \"[[Charles Scribner III|Charlie Scribner]]\" and to Hemingway's literary editor \"[[Maxwell Perkins|Max Perkins]]\",<ref>Hemingway. ''The Old Man and the Sea''. p. 5</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XfPa5B2blv0C&lpg=PR27&dq=the%20old%20man%20and%20the%20sea%20&pg=PR27#v=onepage&q=the%20old%20man%20and%20the%20sea&f=false  |last=Perkins| first=Maxwell |authorlink= Maxwell Perkins | editor1-last=Bruccoli | editor1-first=Matthew J. | editor1-link= Matthew J. Bruccoli| editor2-last=Baughman | editor2-first=Judith | title=The sons of Maxwell Perkins: letters of F. Scott Fitzgerald, Ernest Hemingway, Thomas Wolfe, and their editor | publisher=University of South Carolina Press | year=2004 |page=xxvii | isbn= 1-57003-548-2}}</ref> was featured in ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine on September 1, 1952, and five million copies of the magazine were sold in two days.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Hemingway timeline Any man's life, told truly, is a novel |url=http://www.kcstar.com/hemingway/ehtimeline.shtml |date=June 27, 1999 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]] |publisher=KansasCity.com |accessdate=2009-08-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012220212/http://www.kcstar.com/hemingway/ehtimeline.shtml |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' became a [[Book of the Month Club]] selection, and made Hemingway a celebrity.<ref name=\"Desnoyers p13\">{{Harvnb|Desnoyers|p=13}}</ref> Published in book form on September 1, 1952, the [[first edition]] print run was 50,000 copies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Oliver|1999|p=247}}</ref> The illustrated edition featured black and white pictures by [[Charles Tunnicliffe]] and [[Raymond Sheppard]].<ref name=\"Meyers p489\"/>\n\nIn May 1953, the novel received the [[Pulitzer Prize]]<ref name=\"Meyers p489\">{{Harvnb|Meyers|1985| p=489}}</ref> and was specifically cited when in 1954 he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] which he dedicated to the Cuban people.<ref name=\"TimeNobel\">{{cite journal|title=Heroes:Life with Papa |journal=TIME|issue= |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,857627,00.html |accessdate=2009-12-12 | date=November 8, 1954}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 |url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1954/ |publisher=Nobelprize.org |accessdate=October 4, 2009}}</ref> The success of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' made Hemingway an international celebrity.<ref name=\"Desnoyers p13\"/> ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is taught at schools around the world and continues to earn foreign royalties.<ref name=\"Meyers p485\">{{Harvnb|Meyers|1985| p=485}}</ref>\n\n==Literary significance and criticism==\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' served to reinvigorate Hemingway's literary reputation and prompted a reexamination of his entire body of work. The novel was initially received with much popularity; it restored many readers' confidence in Hemingway's capability as an author. Its publisher, [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner's]], on an early dust jacket, called the novel a \"new classic\", and many critics favorably compared it with such works as [[William Faulkner]]'s short story ''[[Go Down, Moses (book)#.22The Bear.22|The Bear]]'' and [[Herman Melville]]'s novel ''[[Moby-Dick]]''.\n\nSeveral critics note that Santiago hails from the Canary Islands, and that his Spanish origins have an influence in the novella.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref><ref name=\"Hibridaci\u00f3n ling\u00fc\u00edstica\">{{Cite journal | author= Guinea Ulecia, Mercedes | title=Hibridaci\u00f3n ling\u00fc\u00edstica y cultural en autores norteamericanos de origen espa\u00f1ol| journal=Universidad de Huelva | volume=diss. | year=2016 | pages=105-107 http://rabida.uhu.es/dspace/handle/10272/12300 }}</ref><ref name=\"Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy, Jeffrey | title=Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=28 | year=2009 | pages=25-44 https://www.academia.edu/1548905/Santiagos_Expatriation_from_Spain_and_Cultural_Otherness_in_Hemingways_the_Old_Man_and_the_Sea}}</ref> After immigrating to Cuba in his 20s, later in life Santiago dreams about the Canary Islands and mixes Cuban and Peninsular Spanish vocabulary. His biography has many similarities to that of Gregorio Fuentes, Hemingway\u2019s first mate.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref> \n\n[[File:Ernest Hemingway and Henry Strater, Bahamas, 1935.jpg|thumb|Ernest Hemingway and Henry (\"Mike\") Strater with the remaining 500 lbs of an estimated 1000 lb [[marlin]] that was half-eaten by sharks before it could be landed in the Bahamas in 1935. See ''[[Pilar (boat)|Pilar]]'' for details of this episode.]]\n\n[[Gregorio Fuentes]], who many critics believe was an inspiration for Santiago, was a blue-eyed man born on [[Lanzarote]] in the [[Canary Islands]]. After going to sea at age ten on ships that called in African ports, he migrated permanently to Cuba when he was 22. After 82 years in Cuba, Fuentes attempted to reclaim his Spanish citizenship in 2001.<ref name=\"El pescador que inspir\u00f3 a Hemingway \u2018El viejo y el mar\u2019 recupera la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola\">{{cite web | title=El pescador que inspir\u00f3 a Hemingway \u2018El viejo y el mar\u2019 recupera la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola\n| url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2001/01/31/cultura/980908554.html | accessdate =June 7, 2013 }}</ref> Critics have noted that Santiago was also at least 22 when he immigrated from Spain to Cuba, and thus old enough to be considered an immigrant\u2014and a foreigner\u2014in Cuba.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Herlihy |first=Jeffrey |url= https://muse.jhu.edu/article/265112/pdf |title=Eyes the same color as the sea: Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain and Ethnic Otherness and in Hemingway\u2019s the Old Man and the Sea|publisher= Hemingway Review |date= |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref>\n\nHemingway at first planned to use Santiago's story, which became ''The Old Man and the Sea'', as part of an intimacy between mother and son. Relationships in the book relate to the [[Bible]], which he referred to as \"The Sea Book\". Some aspects of it did appear in the posthumously published ''[[Islands in the Stream (Hemingway)|Islands in the Stream]]''. Hemingway mentions the real life experience of an old fisherman almost identical to that of Santiago and his marlin in ''On the Blue Water: A Gulf Stream Letter'' (''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', April 1936).<ref>[http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Old-Man-And-The-Sea/Ernest-Hemingway/9780684830490#excerpt Old Man and the Sea. Introduction: The Ripening of a Masterpiece.]  Simon and Schuster. Retrieved September 29, 2012.</ref><ref>Hemingway, Ernest (edited by William White) (1967). ''By-Line: Ernest Hemingway. Selected articles and dispatches of four decades''. New York: Scribner's.</ref>\n\nJoseph Waldmeir's essay \"''Confiteor Hominem'': Ernest Hemingway's Religion of Man\" is a favorable critical reading of the novel\u2014and one which has defined analytical considerations since. Perhaps the most memorable claim is Waldmeir's answer to the question\u2014What is the book's message?\n<blockquote>The answer assumes a third level on which ''The Old Man and the Sea'' must be read\u2014as a sort of allegorical commentary on all his previous work, by means of which it may be established that the religious overtones of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' are not peculiar to that book among Hemingway's works, and that Hemingway has finally taken the decisive step in elevating what might be called his philosophy of Manhood to the level of a religion.<ref name=\"waldmeir\">{{cite journal\n | last = Joseph Waldmeir\n | title=''Confiteor Hominem'': Ernest Hemingway's Religion of Man\n | journal=Papers of the Michigan Academy of Sciences, Arts, and Letters\n | volume=XLII | year=1957 | pages=349\u2013356\n }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWaldmeir considered the function of the novel's Christian imagery,{{or inline|date=May 2018}} most notably through Hemingway's reference to the [[crucifixion]] of [[Jesus|Christ]] following Santiago's sighting of the sharks that reads:\n\n<blockquote>\"''Ay'',\" he said aloud. There is no translation for this word and perhaps it is just a noise such as a man might make, involuntarily, feeling the nail go through his hands and into the wood.<ref>Hemingway. ''The Old Man and the Sea''. p. 118</ref></blockquote>\n\nOne of the most outspoken critics of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is Robert P. Weeks. His 1962 piece \"Fakery in ''The Old Man and the Sea''\" presents his argument that the novel is a weak and unexpected divergence from the typical, realistic Hemingway (referring to the rest of Hemingway's body of work as \"earlier glories\").<ref name=\"weeks\" /> In juxtaposing this novel against Hemingway's previous works, Weeks contends:\n<blockquote>The difference, however, in the effectiveness with which Hemingway employs this characteristic device in his best work and in ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is illuminating. The work of fiction in which Hemingway devoted the most attention to natural objects, ''The Old Man and the Sea'', is pieced out with an extraordinary quantity of fakery, extraordinary because one would expect to find no inexactness, no romanticizing of natural objects in a writer who loathed [[W. H. Hudson]], could not read [[Henry David Thoreau|Thoreau]], deplored Melville's rhetoric in ''Moby Dick'', and who was himself criticized by other writers, notably Faulkner, for his devotion to the facts and his unwillingness to 'invent.'<ref name=\"weeks\">{{cite journal\n | last = Robert P. Weeks\n | title=Fakery in ''The Old Man and the Sea''\n | journal=College English\n | volume=XXIV | issue=3\n | year=1962 | pages=188\u2013192\n | doi=10.2307/373283\n | jstor=373283\n | first1=Robert P.\n }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1954, Hemingway donated his Nobel Prize gold medal in Literature to the venerated Marian image of [[Our Lady of Charity]]. The Swedish medal was stolen in 1986, but was returned later upon the threat of [[Ra\u00fal Castro]], brother of [[Fidel Castro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/27/cubas-patron-saint-virgin-of-charity_n_1382971.html|title=Huffington Post|date=March 27, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' has been adapted for the screen three times: a [[The Old Man and the Sea (1958 film)|1958 film]] starring [[Spencer Tracy]], a [[The Old Man and the Sea (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]] starring [[Anthony Quinn]], and a [[The Old Man and the Sea (1999 film)|1999 animated short film]]. It is often taught in high schools as a part of the American literature curriculum.\n\nIn 2003, the book was listed at number 173 on the BBC's [[The Big Read]] poll of the UK's 200 \"best-loved novels\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top200_2.shtml \"BBC \u2013 The Big Read\"]. BBC. April 2003, Retrieved August 23, 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite journal |author=The Editors |title=From Ernest Hemingway to the Editors of Life |date=25 August 1952 |journal=Life |publisher=Time Inc |volume=33 |issue=8 |page=124 |issn=0024-3019 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g1YEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA124 |quote=Hemingway's work is a 27,000-word novel called ''The Old Man and the Sea''.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |last=Desnoyers |first=Megan Floyd |title=Ernest Hemingway: A Storyteller's Legacy |work=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library Online Resources |publisher=[[John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum]] |url=http://www.jfklibrary.org/Research/The-Ernest-Hemingway-Collection/Online-Resources/Storytellers-Legacy.aspx?p=1 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meyers |first=Jeffrey |year=1985 |title= Hemingway: A Biography |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] |location=London |isbn=0-333-42126-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Oliver |first=Charles M. |year=1999 |title=Ernest Hemingway A to Z: The Essential Reference to the Life and Work |publisher=Checkmark |location=New York |isbn=0-8160-3467-2 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/ernesthemingwayt0000oliv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Baker |first=Carlos |authorlink=Carlos Baker |year=1972 |title=Hemingway: The Writer as Artist|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |edition=4th |isbn=0-691-01305-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/hemingwaywritera00bake|url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Jobes |editor-first=Katharine T. |year=1968 |title=Twentieth Century Interpretations of The Old Man and the Sea |location=Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey |publisher=Prentice Hall |isbn=0-13-633917-4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mellow |first=James R. |year=1992 |title=Hemingway: A Life Without Consequences |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |location=New York |isbn=0-395-37777-3}}\n* {{cite book |last=Young |first=Philip |title=Ernest Hemingway |year=1952 |location=New York |publisher=Holt, Rinehart, & Winston |isbn=0-8166-0191-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/trent_0116401067404 }}\n* {{cite book | author = Rosella Mamoli Zorzi | author2 = Gianni Moriani | author3= [[Arrigo Cipriani]] | title = In Venice and in the Veneto with Ernest Hemingway | location = Venice | publisher = Supernova | year = 2011 | oclc = 843177468 | isbn = 9788896220474 | pages = III, 62 | language = en,it| series = In Venice and in the Veneto with... | via = [http://archive.is/HSL4o/ archive.is]}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FadedPage|id=20141070|name=The Old Man and the Sea}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110704233506/http://www.life.com/gallery/33122/rare-unseen-hemingway-in-cuba Rare, Unseen: Hemingway in Cuba]\u2014slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine\n* {{cite web\n  | title = Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure: Cuba\n  | publisher = [[PBS]]\n  | url = https://www.pbs.org/hemingwayadventure/cuba.html\n  | accessdate = January 21, 2006\n  }}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[Nobel Prize in Literature]]|before=[[Winston Churchill]]<br>1953\n|after=[[Halld\u00f3r Laxness]]<br>1955\n|years=1954}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{PulitzerPrize Fiction 1951\u20131975}}\n{{Hemingway}}\n{{Billfish}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Old Man And The Sea, The}}\n[[Category:1952 American novels]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Books by Ernest Hemingway]]\n[[Category:Charles Scribner's Sons books]]\n[[Category:Novels about animals]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n[[Category:Novels by Ernest Hemingway]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Fiction-winning works]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:Fish in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Works about old age]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Novel by Ernest Hemingway}} \n{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2011}}\n{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name         = '''The Old Man and the Sea'''\n| image        = Oldmansea.jpg\n| caption      = Original book cover\n| author       = [[Ernest Hemingway]]\n| cover_artist = \n| country      = United States\n| language      = English\n| genre        = Literary Fiction\n| published = 1952 ([[Charles Scribner's Sons]])\n| media_type   = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages        = 127\n| awards = [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]] (1953)<br> [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] (1954)\n| isbn         = 0-684-80122-1\n| oclc         =\n| dewey        =813.52\n| congress = PS3515.E37\n| preceded_by  =\n| followed_by  =}}\n'''''The Old Man and the Sea''''' is a short novel written by the American author [[Ernest Hemingway]] in 1951 in [[Cuba]], and published in 1952.<ref name=\"Time\"/> It was the last major work of fiction by Hemingway that was published during his lifetime. One of his most famous works, it tells the story of Santiago, an aging [[Cubans|Cuban]] [[fisherman]] who struggles with a giant [[marlin]] far out in the [[Gulf Stream]] off the coast of Cuba.<ref name=\"nobel\">{{cite web | title = The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 | work = The Nobel Foundation | url = http://nobelprize.org/literature/laureates/1954/ | accessdate = January 31, 2005 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, ''The Old Man and the Sea'' was awarded the [[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]], and it was cited by the [[Nobel Committee]] as contributing to their awarding of the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] to Hemingway in 1954.<ref name=\"nobel\"/>\n\n==Plot summary==\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' tells the story of a battle between an aging, experienced fisherman, Santiago, and a large [[marlin]]. The story opens with Santiago having gone 84 days without catching a fish, and now being seen as \"''salao''{{-\"}}, the worst form of unluckiness. He is so unlucky that his young apprentice, Manolin, has been forbidden by his parents to sail with him and has been told instead to fish with successful fishermen. The boy visits Santiago's shack each night, hauling his fishing gear, preparing food, talking about American baseball and his favorite player, [[Joe DiMaggio]]. Santiago tells Manolin that on the next day, he will venture far out into the Gulf Stream, north of [[Cuba]] in the [[Straits of Florida]] to fish, confident that his unlucky streak is near its end.\n\nOn the eighty-fifth day of his unlucky streak, Santiago takes his [[skiff]] into the Gulf Stream, sets his lines and by noon, has his bait taken by a big fish that he is sure is a [[marlin]]. Unable to haul in the great marlin, Santiago is instead pulled by the marlin, and two days and nights pass with Santiago holding onto the line. Though wounded by the struggle and in pain, Santiago expresses a compassionate appreciation for his adversary, often referring to him as a brother. He also determines that, because of the fish's great dignity, no one shall deserve to eat the marlin.\n\nOn the third day, the fish begins to circle the skiff. Santiago, worn out and almost delirious, uses all his remaining strength to pull the fish onto its side and stab the marlin with a [[harpoon]]. Santiago straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and heads home, thinking about the high price the fish will bring him at the market and how many people he will feed.\n\nOn his way in to shore, [[shark]]s are attracted to the marlin's blood. Santiago kills a great [[mako shark]] with his harpoon, but he loses the weapon. He makes a new harpoon by strapping his knife to the end of an [[oar]] to help ward off the next line of sharks; five sharks are slain and many others are driven away. But the sharks keep coming, and by nightfall the [[sharks]] have almost devoured the marlin's entire carcass, leaving a skeleton consisting mostly of its backbone, its tail, and its head. Santiago knows that he is destroyed and tells the sharks of how they have killed his dreams. Upon reaching the shore before dawn on the next day, Santiago struggles to his shack, carrying the heavy mast on his shoulder, leaving the fish head and the bones on the shore. Once home, he slumps onto his bed and falls into a deep sleep.\n\nA group of fishermen gather the next day around the boat where the fish's skeleton is still attached. One of the fishermen measures it to be {{convert|18|ft|m}} from nose to tail. Pedrico is given the head of the fish, and the other fishermen tell Manolin to tell the old man how sorry they are. Tourists at the nearby caf\u00e9 mistakenly take it for a shark. The boy, worried about the old man, cries upon finding him safe asleep and at his injured hands. Manolin brings him newspapers and coffee. When the old man wakes, they promise to fish together once again. Upon his return to sleep, Santiago dreams of his youth\u2014of lions on an African beach.\n\n==Background and publication==\n{{quote box | width = 22em | quote = No good book has ever been written that has in it symbols arrived at beforehand and stuck in&nbsp;.... I tried to make a real old man, a real boy, a real sea and a real fish and real sharks. But if I made them good and true enough they would mean many things. | source = Ernest Hemingway in 1954<ref>{{cite magazine| url= http://content.time.com/time/printout/0,8816,935439,00.html | title=Books: An American Storyteller | magazine=TIME| date=December 13, 1954| accessdate=February 1, 2011 }}</ref>}}\n\nWritten in 1951, and published in 1952, ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is Hemingway's final full-length work published during his lifetime. The book, dedicated to \"[[Charles Scribner III|Charlie Scribner]]\" and to Hemingway's literary editor \"[[Maxwell Perkins|Max Perkins]]\",<ref>Hemingway. ''The Old Man and the Sea''. p. 5</ref><ref>{{cite book| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=XfPa5B2blv0C&lpg=PR27&dq=the%20old%20man%20and%20the%20sea%20&pg=PR27#v=onepage&q=the%20old%20man%20and%20the%20sea&f=false  |last=Perkins| first=Maxwell |authorlink= Maxwell Perkins | editor1-last=Bruccoli | editor1-first=Matthew J. | editor1-link= Matthew J. Bruccoli| editor2-last=Baughman | editor2-first=Judith | title=The sons of Maxwell Perkins: letters of F. Scott Fitzgerald, Ernest Hemingway, Thomas Wolfe, and their editor | publisher=University of South Carolina Press | year=2004 |page=xxvii | isbn= 1-57003-548-2}}</ref> was featured in ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine on September 1, 1952, and five million copies of the magazine were sold in two days.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Hemingway timeline Any man's life, told truly, is a novel |url=http://www.kcstar.com/hemingway/ehtimeline.shtml |date=June 27, 1999 |work=[[The Kansas City Star]] |publisher=KansasCity.com |accessdate=2009-08-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012220212/http://www.kcstar.com/hemingway/ehtimeline.shtml |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' became a [[Book of the Month Club]] selection, and made Hemingway a celebrity.<ref name=\"Desnoyers p13\">{{Harvnb|Desnoyers|p=13}}</ref> Published in book form on September 1, 1952, the [[first edition]] print run was 50,000 copies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Oliver|1999|p=247}}</ref> The illustrated edition featured black and white pictures by [[Charles Tunnicliffe]] and [[Raymond Sheppard]].<ref name=\"Meyers p489\"/>\n\nIn May 1953, the novel received the [[Pulitzer Prize]]<ref name=\"Meyers p489\">{{Harvnb|Meyers|1985| p=489}}</ref> and was specifically cited when in 1954 he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] which he dedicated to the Cuban people.<ref name=\"TimeNobel\">{{cite journal|title=Heroes:Life with Papa |journal=TIME|issue= |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,857627,00.html |accessdate=2009-12-12 | date=November 8, 1954}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Nobel Prize in Literature 1954 |url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1954/ |publisher=Nobelprize.org |accessdate=October 4, 2009}}</ref> The success of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' made Hemingway an international celebrity.<ref name=\"Desnoyers p13\"/> ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is taught at schools around the world and continues to earn foreign royalties.<ref name=\"Meyers p485\">{{Harvnb|Meyers|1985| p=485}}</ref>\n\n==Literary significance and criticism==\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' served to reinvigorate Hemingway's literary reputation and prompted a reexamination of his entire body of work. The novel was initially received with much popularity; it restored many readers' confidence in Hemingway's capability as an author. Its publisher, [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner's]], on an early dust jacket, called the novel a \"new classic\", and many critics favorably compared it with such works as [[William Faulkner]]'s short story ''[[Go Down, Moses (book)#.22The Bear.22|The Bear]]'' and [[Herman Melville]]'s novel ''[[Moby-Dick]]''.\n\nSeveral critics note that Santiago hails from the Canary Islands, and that his Spanish origins have an influence in the novella.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref><ref name=\"Hibridaci\u00f3n ling\u00fc\u00edstica\">{{Cite journal | author= Guinea Ulecia, Mercedes | title=Hibridaci\u00f3n ling\u00fc\u00edstica y cultural en autores norteamericanos de origen espa\u00f1ol| journal=Universidad de Huelva | volume=diss. | year=2016 | pages=105-107 http://rabida.uhu.es/dspace/handle/10272/12300 }}</ref><ref name=\"Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy, Jeffrey | title=Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=28 | year=2009 | pages=25-44 https://www.academia.edu/1548905/Santiagos_Expatriation_from_Spain_and_Cultural_Otherness_in_Hemingways_the_Old_Man_and_the_Sea}}</ref> After immigrating to Cuba in his 20s, later in life Santiago dreams about the Canary Islands and mixes Cuban and Peninsular Spanish vocabulary. His biography has many similarities to that of Gregorio Fuentes, Hemingway\u2019s first mate.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref> \n\n[[File:Ernest Hemingway and Henry Strater, Bahamas, 1935.jpg|thumb|Ernest Hemingway and Henry (\"Mike\") Strater with the remaining 500 lbs of an estimated 1000 lb [[marlin]] that was half-eaten by sharks before it could be landed in the Bahamas in 1935. See ''[[Pilar (boat)|Pilar]]'' for details of this episode.]]\n\n[[Gregorio Fuentes]], who many critics believe was an inspiration for Santiago, was a blue-eyed man born on [[Lanzarote]] in the [[Canary Islands]]. After going to sea at age ten on ships that called in African ports, he migrated permanently to Cuba when he was 22. After 82 years in Cuba, Fuentes attempted to reclaim his Spanish citizenship in 2001.<ref name=\"El pescador que inspir\u00f3 a Hemingway \u2018El viejo y el mar\u2019 recupera la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola\">{{cite web | title=El pescador que inspir\u00f3 a Hemingway \u2018El viejo y el mar\u2019 recupera la nacionalidad espa\u00f1ola\n| url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2001/01/31/cultura/980908554.html | accessdate =June 7, 2013 }}</ref> Critics have noted that Santiago was also at least 22 when he immigrated from Spain to Cuba, and thus old enough to be considered an immigrant\u2014and a foreigner\u2014in Cuba.<ref name=\"Cuba in Hemingway\">{{Cite journal | author=Herlihy-Mera, Jeffrey | title=Cuba in Hemingway | journal=The Hemingway Review | volume=36 | year=2017 | pages=8-41 https://www.academia.edu/33255402/Cuba_in_Hemingway }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Herlihy |first=Jeffrey |url= https://muse.jhu.edu/article/265112/pdf |title=Eyes the same color as the sea: Santiago\u2019s Expatriation from Spain and Ethnic Otherness and in Hemingway\u2019s the Old Man and the Sea|publisher= Hemingway Review |date= |accessdate=2015-04-17}}</ref>\n\nHemingway at first planned to use Santiago's story, which became ''The Old Man and the Sea'', as part of an intimacy between mother and son. Relationships in the book relate to the [[Bible]], which he referred to as \"The Sea Book\". Some aspects of it did appear in the posthumously published ''[[Islands in the Stream (Hemingway)|Islands in the Stream]]''. Hemingway mentions the real life experience of an old fisherman almost identical to that of Santiago and his marlin in ''On the Blue Water: A Gulf Stream Letter'' (''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', April 1936).<ref>[http://www.simonandschuster.com/books/Old-Man-And-The-Sea/Ernest-Hemingway/9780684830490#excerpt Old Man and the Sea. Introduction: The Ripening of a Masterpiece.]  Simon and Schuster. Retrieved September 29, 2012.</ref><ref>Hemingway, Ernest (edited by William White) (1967). ''By-Line: Ernest Hemingway. Selected articles and dispatches of four decades''. New York: Scribner's.</ref>\n\nJoseph Waldmeir's essay \"''Confiteor Hominem'': Ernest Hemingway's Religion of Man\" is a favorable critical reading of the novel\u2014and one which has defined analytical considerations since. Perhaps the most memorable claim is Waldmeir's answer to the question\u2014What is the book's message?\n<blockquote>The answer assumes a third level on which ''The Old Man and the Sea'' must be read\u2014as a sort of allegorical commentary on all his previous work, by means of which it may be established that the religious overtones of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' are not peculiar to that book among Hemingway's works, and that Hemingway has finally taken the decisive step in elevating what might be called his philosophy of Manhood to the level of a religion.<ref name=\"waldmeir\">{{cite journal\n | last = Joseph Waldmeir\n | title=''Confiteor Hominem'': Ernest Hemingway's Religion of Man\n | journal=Papers of the Michigan Academy of Sciences, Arts, and Letters\n | volume=XLII | year=1957 | pages=349\u2013356\n }}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWaldmeir considered the function of the novel's Christian imagery,{{or inline|date=May 2018}} most notably through Hemingway's reference to the [[crucifixion]] of [[Jesus|Christ]] following Santiago's sighting of the sharks that reads:\n\n<blockquote>\"''Ay'',\" he said aloud. There is no translation for this word and perhaps it is just a noise such as a man might make, involuntarily, feeling the nail go through his hands and into the wood.<ref>Hemingway. ''The Old Man and the Sea''. p. 118</ref></blockquote>\n\nOne of the most outspoken critics of ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is Robert P. Weeks. His 1962 piece \"Fakery in ''The Old Man and the Sea''\" presents his argument that the novel is a weak and unexpected divergence from the typical, realistic Hemingway (referring to the rest of Hemingway's body of work as \"earlier glories\").<ref name=\"weeks\" /> In juxtaposing this novel against Hemingway's previous works, Weeks contends:\n<blockquote>The difference, however, in the effectiveness with which Hemingway employs this characteristic device in his best work and in ''The Old Man and the Sea'' is illuminating. The work of fiction in which Hemingway devoted the most attention to natural objects, ''The Old Man and the Sea'', is pieced out with an extraordinary quantity of fakery, extraordinary because one would expect to find no inexactness, no romanticizing of natural objects in a writer who loathed [[W. H. Hudson]], could not read [[Henry David Thoreau|Thoreau]], deplored Melville's rhetoric in ''Moby Dick'', and who was himself criticized by other writers, notably Faulkner, for his devotion to the facts and his unwillingness to 'invent.'<ref name=\"weeks\">{{cite journal\n | last = Robert P. Weeks\n | title=Fakery in ''The Old Man and the Sea''\n | journal=College English\n | volume=XXIV | issue=3\n | year=1962 | pages=188\u2013192\n | doi=10.2307/373283\n | jstor=373283\n | first1=Robert P.\n }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 1954, Hemingway donated his Nobel Prize gold medal in Literature to the venerated Marian image of [[Our Lady of Charity]]. The Swedish medal was stolen in 1986, but was returned later upon the threat of [[Ra\u00fal Castro]], brother of [[Fidel Castro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/27/cubas-patron-saint-virgin-of-charity_n_1382971.html|title=Huffington Post|date=March 27, 2012|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''The Old Man and the Sea'' has been adapted for the screen three times: a [[The Old Man and the Sea (1958 film)|1958 film]] starring [[Spencer Tracy]], a [[The Old Man and the Sea (miniseries)|1990 miniseries]] starring [[Anthony Quinn]], and a [[The Old Man and the Sea (1999 film)|1999 animated short film]]. It is often taught in high schools as a part of the American literature curriculum.\n\nIn 2003, the book was listed at number 173 on the BBC's [[The Big Read]] poll of the UK's 200 \"best-loved novels\".<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/bigread/top200_2.shtml \"BBC \u2013 The Big Read\"]. BBC. April 2003, Retrieved August 23, 2017</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite journal |author=The Editors |title=From Ernest Hemingway to the Editors of Life |date=25 August 1952 |journal=Life |publisher=Time Inc |volume=33 |issue=8 |page=124 |issn=0024-3019 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g1YEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA124 |quote=Hemingway's work is a 27,000-word novel called ''The Old Man and the Sea''.}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |last=Desnoyers |first=Megan Floyd |title=Ernest Hemingway: A Storyteller's Legacy |work=John F. Kennedy Presidential Library Online Resources |publisher=[[John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum]] |url=http://www.jfklibrary.org/Research/The-Ernest-Hemingway-Collection/Online-Resources/Storytellers-Legacy.aspx?p=1 |accessdate=December 9, 2011 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meyers |first=Jeffrey |year=1985 |title= Hemingway: A Biography |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] |location=London |isbn=0-333-42126-4 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Oliver |first=Charles M. |year=1999 |title=Ernest Hemingway A to Z: The Essential Reference to the Life and Work |publisher=Checkmark |location=New York |isbn=0-8160-3467-2 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/ernesthemingwayt0000oliv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Baker |first=Carlos |authorlink=Carlos Baker |year=1972 |title=Hemingway: The Writer as Artist|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |edition=4th |isbn=0-691-01305-5 |url=https://archive.org/details/hemingwaywritera00bake|url-access=registration }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last=Jobes |editor-first=Katharine T. |year=1968 |title=Twentieth Century Interpretations of The Old Man and the Sea |location=Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey |publisher=Prentice Hall |isbn=0-13-633917-4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Mellow |first=James R. |year=1992 |title=Hemingway: A Life Without Consequences |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |location=New York |isbn=0-395-37777-3}}\n* {{cite book |last=Young |first=Philip |title=Ernest Hemingway |year=1952 |location=New York |publisher=Holt, Rinehart, & Winston |isbn=0-8166-0191-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/trent_0116401067404 }}\n* {{cite book | author = Rosella Mamoli Zorzi | author2 = Gianni Moriani | author3= [[Arrigo Cipriani]] | title = In Venice and in the Veneto with Ernest Hemingway | location = Venice | publisher = Supernova | year = 2011 | oclc = 843177468 | isbn = 9788896220474 | pages = III, 62 | language = en,it| series = In Venice and in the Veneto with... | via = [http://archive.is/HSL4o/ archive.is]}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FadedPage|id=20141070|name=The Old Man and the Sea}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110704233506/http://www.life.com/gallery/33122/rare-unseen-hemingway-in-cuba Rare, Unseen: Hemingway in Cuba]\u2014slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine\n* {{cite web\n  | title = Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure: Cuba\n  | publisher = [[PBS]]\n  | url = https://www.pbs.org/hemingwayadventure/cuba.html\n  | accessd