 by {{NYCS|6}} trains at all times, [[6d (New York City Subway service)|&#x3C;6&#x3E;]] trains during weekdays in the peak direction, and {{NYCS|4}} trains during late night hours.\n\n== History ==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 4-tracked local station\n|1=Grand Central\u201342nd Street\n|l1=42 St\n|2=28th Street\n|l2=28 St\n|code=IRT Lexington Avenue Line\n|color=Lexington\n|textcolor=white\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\nConstruction started on the [[Early history of the IRT subway|first IRT line]] in 1900.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/fiftyyearsrapid00walkgoog|title=Fifty Years of Rapid Transit \u2014 1864 to 1917|last1=Walker|first1=James Blaine|date=1918|publisher=Law Printing|isbn=|location=New York, N.Y.|pages=|accessdate=November 6, 2016}}</ref>{{Rp|162\u2013191}} The part of the line from City Hall to just south of 42nd Street was part of the original [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]] line, opened on October 27, 1904 including a local station at 33rd Street.<ref name=\"145th\"/>\n\nOn April 13, 1948, the platform extensions to accommodate ten-car trains at this station along with those at [[23rd Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|23rd Street]], and [[28th Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|28th Street]] were opened for use.<ref name=\"BOT-1949\">{{Cite book|title=Report for the three and one-half years ending June 30, 1949.|date=1949|publisher=New York City Board of Transportation|hdl = 2027/mdp.39015023094926}}</ref>\n\nOn December 27, 1948, a new entrance to the station at 32nd Street opened for use.<ref name=\"BOT-1949\" />\n\n=== Express stop proposals ===\nIt has been proposed several times\u2013by the IRT and members of the public\u2013that this station be rebuilt as an express stop to reduce overcrowding at the [[Grand Central\u201342nd Street (New York City Subway)|Grand Central\u201342nd Street]] station one stop to the north. It was estimated that the extra time spent by express trains at 33rd Street would be offset by the reduced dwell times at Grand Central.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WNHI3SkuyX0C&pg=PA459&dq=33rd+street+express+station#v=onepage|title=Supreme Court Appellate Division-Second Department|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=458\u2013460|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aN0hAAAAMAAJ&dq=33rd+street+convert+express+station&q=33rd+street|title=ERA Headlights|date=1956|publisher=Electric Railroaders Association.|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Station layout ==\n{{NYCS Platform Layout IRT Lexington Avenue Line/Park Avenue South stations}}\n\nThere are four tracks and two [[side platform]]s, with the express tracks in the middle. The express tracks stay level, while the local tracks slowly incline from south to north to allow for the easier deceleration of local trains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nycsubway.org/wiki/Chapter_03._General_Arrangement_for_Construction|title=The New York Rapid Transit Railway Extensions|last=Lavis|first=Fred|date=1914|website=nycsubway.org|publisher=Engineering News|access-date=May 31, 2018}}</ref> North of the station, the two pairs of tracks in each direction separate into different tunnels because of the presence of the [[Murray Hill Tunnel]], which runs under the center of this section of Park Avenue. The station was renovated in the late 1990s or early 2000s, and contains eagle plaques similar to those at [[Brooklyn Bridge\u2013City Hall (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)|Brooklyn Bridge\u2013City Hall]]. The plaques contain the numerals \"33\". [[Fare control]] is at the platform level. The station has been on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] since 2004.<ref name=\"focus\"/>\n\n{{Midtown Manhattan subway cross section}}\n===Exits===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n! Exit location<ref name=maps>{{cite web|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Union Square / Gramercy|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M07_UnionSq-Gramercy_2015.pdf|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=August 6, 2015|date=2015}}</ref>\n! width=50px| Number of exits\n! Platform served\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| NW corner of Park Avenue and 33rd Street\n| 1\n| Southbound\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| SW corner of Park Avenue and 33rd Street\n| 1\n| Southbound\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| NE corner of Park Avenue and 33rd Street\n| 1\n| Northbound\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| SE corner of Park Avenue and 33rd Street\n| 1\n| Northbound\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| SE corner of Park Avenue S and 32nd Street\n| 2\n| Northbound\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| SW corner of Park Avenue S and 32nd Street\n| 2\n| Southbound\n|}\n\n== Image gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:33rd Street IRT 002.JPG|Faience plaque by Heins & LaFarge / Grueby Faience Company, 1904.\nFile:33rd Street IRT 003.JPG|Tile name tablet by Heins & LaFarge / John H. Parry Co., 1904.\nFile:33rd Street IRT 001.JPG|\nFile:33rd Street IRT 006.JPG|\nFile:33rd Street IRT 005.JPG|The unique fare control ironwork and Art for Transit installation on the columns \nFile:33d Lex Downtown stair jeh.JPG|Southbound street stairs\nFile:33rd Street IRT 1905.jpg|33rd Street station in 1905\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Lee Stokey. ''Subway Ceramics: A History and Iconography''. 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-9635486-1-0}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat|33rd Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?5:3102|IRT East Side Line|33rd Street}}\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20131219141200/http://www.stationreporter.net/4train.htm 4 Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20120204052106/http://www.stationreporter.net/6train.htm 6 Train]\n* Forgotten NY \u2014 [http://forgotten-ny.com/2006/01/the-original-28-part-1-a-look-at-the-artwork-from-the-nycs-first-28-stations-opened-october-27-1904-2/ Original 28 - NYC's First 28 Subway Stations]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606071553/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=6&station=13&xdev=1349 33rd Street (IRT Lexington Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ll=40.745973,-73.982706&spn=0.005243,0.009645&layer=c&cbll=40.745929,-73.982605&panoid=V2Jj4JDYGwbHbtBwzKJvSQ&cbp=12,209.12,,0,8.68&t=m&z=17 32nd Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.746534,-73.981816&spn=0.003845,0.013433&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.746522,-73.981667&panoid=UDfq6YH167F-l0xg_tne4w&cbp=12,86.51,,0,0.69 33rd Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?ll=40.746173,-73.981745&spn=0.001546,0.002905&t=m&z=19&layer=c&cbll=40.746173,-73.981745&panoid=5nCHjLENeF4AAAQfCUbVVw&cbp=12,332,,0,6.4 downtown platform from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l6=y|l6x=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|lexington=yes}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:33rd Street (Irt Lexington Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:Murray Hill, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:IRT Lexington Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:Railway and subway stations on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n[[Category:1904 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Park Avenue|*]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City interior landmarks]]\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "format ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/33rd_Street_station_(IRT_Lexington_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "Virginia Walbot", "text_new": "'''Virginia Walbot''' (born 1946) is an [[United States|American]] [[agriculturalist]] and [[botanist]] who is a professor<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref> in the Department of Biology at [[Stanford University]]. She was a member of a team that developed a new sweet corn.<ref>[Wang, Dongxue, David S. Skibbe, and Virginia Walbot. \"''Maize Male Sterile 8 (Ms8), A Putative \u0392-1,3-Galactosyltransferase, Modulates Cell Division, Expansion, And Differentiation During Early Maize Anther Development.\" Plant Reproduction 26.4 (2013): 329-338. Academic Search Premier. Web. 1 Feb. 2014.]</ref>  She co-authored an article for corn farming in the 4th issue, volume 26 of ''Plant Reproduction'' titled \"Maize Male sterile 8 (Ms8), a putative \u03b2-1,3-galactosyltransferase, modulates cell division, expansion, and differentiation during early maize anther development\".\n\n==Life==\nWalbot first began working with corn when she used to help grow and sell it on her family's farm in Southern California. Later in the 1970s she began her interest in corn when she met Barbara McClintock, who also worked with corn. That is when Walbot began visiting McClintock's lab in Cold Spring Harbor and when she became devoted to the studies of the sex life of corn.\n\nIn 1967, Walbot received a BA degree in biology at Stanford University. In 1969\u20131972, attended Yale to work on embryogenesis to receive an M.Phil. and Ph.D. She attended the University of Georgia to postdoctoral work. She became a faculty Member at Washington University in St. Louis. Later Walbot returned to Stanford as a professor in the Department of Biology.\n\nWalbot first worked with maize while working with Ed Coe in the University of Missouri.\n\nWalbot participates in societies including the American Society for Cell Biology, AAAS, AIBS, Genetics Society, and International Society for Plant Molecular Biology<ref>{{cite web|title=Hageman Lecturer|url=http://www.k-state.edu/bmb/seminars/hageman/2001-walbot.html|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPublished two books, ''Developmental Biology'' in 1987 and ''The Maize Handbook'' in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://web.stanford.edu/~walbot/cv/cv_walbot.pdf|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nWalbot has published a total of 126 journal articles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford School of Medicine|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot?tab=publications|website=Stanford|accessdate=2014-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative appointments==\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot?tab=bio|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref>*Elected to the Steering Committee of the Faculty Senate, Stanford (2009 - 2011)\n*Elected to Faculty Senate, Stanford (2009\u20132011)\n*Elected to Faculty Senate, Stanford (1999\u20132001)\n*Committee on Committees, Stanford (2000\u20132001)\n*Committee on Research, Stanford (2003\u20132005)\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*Cooresponding Member, Mexican Academy of Sciences (2004)\n*Hageman Lectureship, Kansas State University (2001)\n*Joan V. Wood Lectureship, Indiana University (1999)\n*Explorer Award, National Geographic Society (1998)\n*Eppley Award, Eppley Foundation (1993)\n*Fellow, Guggenheim Foundation (1987)\n*Belk Award, Miami University of Ohio (1985)\n*Fellow, American Assn. Advancement of Science (1981)\n*Postdoctoral Fellowship, NIH (1972\u20131975)\n*Predoctoral fellowship, NSF (1969\u20131972)<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.stanford.edu/~walbot/ The Walbot Lab at Stanford University]\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_18825679|title=Stanford scientist studies the sex life of corn|author=Lisa M. Krieger|date= 4 September 2011|work=San Jose Mercury News}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walbot, Virginia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American agriculturalists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Stanford University Department of Biology faculty]]\n", "text_old": "'''Virginia Walbot''' born in 1946, is an [[United States|American]] [[agriculturalist]] and [[botanist]] who is a professor<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref> in the Department of Biology at [[Stanford University]]. She was a member of a team that developed a new sweet corn.<ref>[Wang, Dongxue, David S. Skibbe, and Virginia Walbot. \"''Maize Male Sterile 8 (Ms8), A Putative \u0392-1,3-Galactosyltransferase, Modulates Cell Division, Expansion, And Differentiation During Early Maize Anther Development.\" Plant Reproduction 26.4 (2013): 329-338. Academic Search Premier. Web. 1 Feb. 2014.]</ref>  She co-authored an article for corn farming in the 4th issue, volume 26 of Plant Reproduction titled \"Maize Male sterile 8 (Ms8), a putative \u03b2-1,3-galactosyltransferase, modulates cell division, expansion, and differentiation during early maize anther development.''\"\n\n==Life==\nVirginia Walbot first began working with corn when she used to help grow and sell it on her family's farm in Southern California. Later in the 1970s she began her interest in corn when she met Barbara McClintock, who also worked with corn. That is when Walbot began visiting McClintock's lab in Cold Spring Harbor and when she became devoted to the studies of the sex life of corn.\n\nIn 1967, Virginia Walbot received a BA degree in Biology at Stanford University. In 1969-1972, attended Yale to work on embryogenesis to receive a M. Phil and PH.D. Dr. Walbot attended the University of Georgia to postdoctoral work. She became a faculty Member at Washington University in St. Louis. Later Dr. Walbot returned to Stanford as a professor in the Department of Biology.\n\nDr. Walbot first worked with maize while working with Ed Coe in the University of Missouri.\n\nDr. Walbot participates in societies including the American Society for Cell Biology, AAAS, AIBS, Genetics Society, and International Society for Plant Molecular Biology<ref>{{cite web|title=Hageman Lecturer|url=http://www.k-state.edu/bmb/seminars/hageman/2001-walbot.html|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nPublished two books, Developmental Biology in 1987 and The Maize Handbook in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://web.stanford.edu/~walbot/cv/cv_walbot.pdf|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nVirginia Walbot has published a total of 126 journal articles.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stanford School of Medicine|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot?tab=publications|website=Stanford|accessdate=2014-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Administrative Appointments==\n\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot?tab=bio|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref>*Elected to the Steering Committee of the Faculty Senate, Stanford (2009 - 2011)\n*Elected to Faculty Senate, Stanford (2009 - 2011)\n*Elected to Faculty Senate, Stanford (1999 - 2001)\n*Committee on Committees, Stanford (2000 - 2001)\n*Committee on Research, Stanford (2003 - 2005)\n\n==Honors & Awards==\n*Cooresponding Member, Mexican Academy of Sciences (2004)\n*Hageman Lectureship, Kansas State University (2001)\n*Joan V. Wood Lectureship, Indiana University (1999)\n*Explorer Award, National Geographic Society (1998)\n*Eppley Award, Eppley Foundation (1993)\n*Fellow, Guggenheim Foundation (1987)\n*Belk Award, Miami University of Ohio (1985)\n*Fellow, American Assn. Advancement of Science (1981)\n*Postdoctoral Fellowship, NIH (1972-1975)\n*Predoctoral fellowship, NSF (1969-1972)<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Walbot|url=https://med.stanford.edu/profiles/virginia-walbot|website=Stanford School of Medicine}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.stanford.edu/~walbot/ The Walbot Lab at Stanford University]\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/ci_18825679|title=Stanford scientist studies the sex life of corn|author=Lisa M. Krieger|date= 4 September 2011|work=San Jose Mercury News}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walbot, Virginia}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American agriculturalists]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Stanford University Department of Biology faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct, italics, use surname", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virginia_Walbot"}
